solutions.content:
I've included my solution with comments below.

The key thing that helped me come to a solution to this problem was realizing that I didn't actually care what characters were used when doing replace and insert operations to satisfy a constraint.  If upper case constraint hasn't been satisfied, then you know that will take exactly 1 step (either an insert or a replace).  This is true for the lowercase and digit constraints as well.  The character used when inserting or replacing is completely irrelevant.

Max length & the repeat constraints are the most interesting aspects of this challenge.  If you take those out, this problem becomes very simple.  That might be a good way to initially think about the problem.  See code with comments for more on how to tackle the repeat and max length constraints.

```
public class Solution {
    private const int MIN_LENGTH = 6;
    private const int MAX_LENGTH = 20;
    private const int MAX_REPEAT_LENGTH = 3;

    public int StrongPasswordChecker(string password) {
        // Approach:
        //     Determine what aspects of the password need to be changed and then determine how to
        //     best combine these actions in a way that the fewest actions possible are used.

        // Find all repeat char sequences and also track if we need to fix the lowercase, uppercase, and digit
        // constraints at the same time
        bool hasLowerCase = false;
        bool hasUpperCase = false;
        bool hasDigit = false;
        List<int> repeatCharCounts = new List<int>();
        for (int i = 0; i < password.Length; ++i) {
            char c = password[i];
            hasLowerCase |= c >= 'a' && c <= 'z';
            hasUpperCase |= c >= 'A' && c <= 'Z';
            hasDigit |= c >= '0' && c <= '9';
            int repeatLen = 1;
            while (i + 1 < password.Length && password[i + 1] == c) {
                ++i;
                ++repeatLen;
            }
            if (repeatLen >= MAX_REPEAT_LENGTH) {
                repeatCharCounts.Add(repeatLen);
            }
        }

        // Optimize deletions by first exploring char sequences and deleting from the one that is closest to
        // the mod boundary
        int deletions = 0;
        int passwordCount = password.Length;
        if (passwordCount > MAX_LENGTH) {
            repeatCharCounts = repeatCharCounts.OrderBy(x => x % MAX_REPEAT_LENGTH).ToList();
            while (passwordCount > MAX_LENGTH && repeatCharCounts.Any()) {
                --passwordCount;
                ++deletions;
                var sequence = repeatCharCounts[0];
                if (sequence == MAX_REPEAT_LENGTH) {
                    // This sequence no longer violates the repeat constraint, so remove it
                    repeatCharCounts.RemoveAt(0);
                } else if (sequence % MAX_REPEAT_LENGTH == 0) {
                    // This sequence is at the mod boundary, so after subtracting 1 move it to
                    // the back of the list since it's now the furthest from the mod boundary
                    repeatCharCounts.RemoveAt(0);
                    repeatCharCounts.Insert(repeatCharCounts.Count, sequence - 1);
                } else {
                    // This sequence is now closer to the mod boundary, so just update it in place
                    repeatCharCounts[0] = sequence - 1;
                }
            }
        }
        // Add remaining necessary deletions
        if (passwordCount > MAX_LENGTH) {
            deletions += passwordCount - MAX_LENGTH;
        }

        // Determine how many inserts / replaces are necessary to resolve repeating char sequences
        int repeatInsertsAndReplaces = 0;
        while (repeatCharCounts.Any()) {
            int count = repeatCharCounts[0];
            repeatCharCounts.RemoveAt(0);
            repeatInsertsAndReplaces += count / MAX_REPEAT_LENGTH;
        }

        // Determine how many inserts / replaces are necessary for the lowercase, upper case, digit,
        // and minimum char constraints
        int requiredInsertsOrReplace = (hasLowerCase ? 0 : 1) + (hasUpperCase ? 0 : 1) + (hasDigit ? 0 : 1);
        requiredInsertsOrReplace = password.Length < MIN_LENGTH
            ? Math.Max(MIN_LENGTH - password.Length, requiredInsertsOrReplace)
            : requiredInsertsOrReplace;

        // Put everything together for the fewest steps required to make the password strong
        int steps = Math.Max(requiredInsertsOrReplace, repeatInsertsAndReplaces) + deletions;
        return steps;
    }
}
```

