Below is my thought process, not sure if it is the best but it works. I hope it helps! Please vote if you find this helpful.

Consider these following scenarios.

1. The password has all needed components such as lower, upper case letters and digits, and it is within the size range. The only thing we need to worry about is to **tweak the consecutive duplicate letters of 3 or more**. For that, we just need to change one out of each 3 letters. 

It is an easy O(N) scan to find all sectons of consecutive duplicate letters of 3 or more.

```
        vector<int> sections;
        int t = 0;
        char last = 0;
        for(char c:password) {
            if(c!=last) {
                if(t>=3) sections.push_back(t);
                t = 0;
                last = c;
                if(c>='a' && c<='z') hasLower = true;
                else if(c>='A' && c<='Z') hasUpper = true;
                else if(c>='0' && c<='9') hasDigit = true;
            }
            t++;
        }
        if(t>=3) sections.push_back(t);
```

Once we put the sections in a vector, it is easy to add moves by modifying each section by changing 1 of each 3 characters.
```
for(int s:sections) moves += s/3;
```

2. Now add on top of the above scenario, we want to **ensure we have all needed components**. That means everytime we make changes to the duplicate sections, we will take the opportunity to add whatever missing components. Here, I use a lambda function so it is easier to understand and re-use. And, after processing all the sections, we will still need to check once more and add missing components. This function takes an input as how many opportunities I can use, and returns the actual moves used for ensuring. We will be re-using this function throughout the process again in future modifications. 

```
auto ensureComponents = [&](int available) { // available means available opportunities
    int changed = 0;
    while(available-->0) {
	    if(!hasLower) hasLower = true;
		else if(!hasUpper) hasUpper = true;
		else if(!hasDigit) hasDigit = true;
		else return changed;
		changed++;
	}
	return changed; // actual components added
};

for(int s:sections) {
	moves += s/3;
	ensureComponents(s/3);
}

moves += ensureComponents(3); // giving 3 more opportunites in case we need, only adding what we actually used
```

3. Now consider the scenario where **we don't have enough (6) characters**. Again, we will take opportunities to address when we address the duplicate characters. Also, check at the end. We can do this by using the new character to chop off two from the duplicate section. And the loop will become looking like below, assuming n stores the length of the password.

```
for(int s:sections) {
	while(n<6 && s>=3) {
		moves++;
		n++;
		s-=2;  // adding a character to chop off two characters from this sectoin
		ensureComponents(1);  // the adding move can also be an opportunity for ensuring we have all variety
	}

	moves += s/3;
	ensureComponents(s/3);
}

moves += max(0, 6 - n);  // after processing sections, still not enough, then add here
ensureComponents(max(0, 6-n)); // these moves are also opportunities for adding missing components
moves += ensureComponents(3);
```

4. Now we need to consider the scenario where **we have more that 20 characters**. This is a little different. We will want to process as much deletion as possible before we start processing the duplicate characters, so we don't waste moves. What groups should we prioritize to remove characters from? We know that we will be changing 1 out of each 3 duplicates. So, if any group is exactly multiples of 3, then removing 1 character from them means we hit two birds with one stone. We should prioritize groups with `s%3==0`, after that for groups with `s%3==1`, we will need to remove two from the 3 to actually make a difference. And at last, for groups with `s%3==2`, we will remove 3 each time to be able to make a difference. Below is how I did the removing part.

```
if(!sections.empty()) {
	sort(sections.begin(), sections.end(), [](int a, int b){return a%3<b%3;}); // prioritizing based on s%3

	int reduced = 0;
	int i = 0;
	while(n>20) {
		int r = sections[i] % 3;
		if (sections[i]>=3 && n>20+r) {
			sections[i]-=r+1;
			moves+=r+1;
			reduced+=r+1;
			n-=r+1;
		}
		if(++i==sections.size()) {
			if (reduced==0) break; // a full scan without reduction
			i-=sections.size();
			reduced = 0;
		}
	}
}
	.
	.
	.
// at the end
moves += max(0, n - 20);
```

5. Now **putting everything together**

```
    int strongPasswordChecker(string password) {
        bool hasLower = false;
        bool hasUpper = false;
        bool hasDigit = false;
        int n = password.length();

        vector<int> sections;
        int t = 0;
        char last = 0;
        for(char c:password) {
            if(c!=last) {
                if(t>=3) sections.push_back(t);
                t = 0;
                last = c;
                if(c>='a' && c<='z') hasLower = true;
                else if(c>='A' && c<='Z') hasUpper = true;
                else if(c>='0' && c<='9') hasDigit = true;
            }
            t++;
        }
        if(t>=3) sections.push_back(t);

        int moves = 0;

        if(!sections.empty()) {
            sort(sections.begin(), sections.end(), [](int a, int b){return a%3 < b%3;});

            int reduced = 0;
            int i = 0;
            while(n>20) {
                int r = sections[i] % 3;
                if (sections[i]>=3 && n>20+r) {
                    sections[i]-=r+1;
                    moves+=r+1;
                    reduced+=r+1;
                    n-=r+1;
                }
                if(++i==sections.size()) {
                    if (reduced==0) break; // a full scan without reduction
                    i-=sections.size();
                    reduced = 0;
                }
            }
        }

        auto ensureComponents = [&](int available) {
            int changed = 0;
            while(available-->0) {
                if(!hasLower) hasLower = true;
                else if(!hasUpper) hasUpper = true;
                else if(!hasDigit) hasDigit = true;
                else return changed;
                changed++;
            }
            return changed;
        };

        for(int s:sections) {
            while(n<6 && s>=3) {
                moves++;
                n++;
                s-=2;
                ensureComponents(1);
            }

            moves += s/3;
            ensureComponents(s/3);
        }

        moves += max(0, 6 - n);
        ensureComponents(max(0, 6-n));
        moves += ensureComponents(3);
        moves += max(0, n - 20);

        return moves;
    }
