# Intuition
Outside trivial checks we must count steps that overlap to make the password strong.

# Approach
First just handle simple contraints, adding lower / upper / digit, at most three steps to solve this. If too short just add these, we can always add them in a way that doesn't cause other contraints to trigger. Count all repeating chars, calculation for overlap is easy - for every three repeating chars we need to add / replace a character, always using the missing one from previous contraints if applicable.

The non-obvious part to calculate is if we have a password that is too long, we can trim the repeating char groups to disappear while shortening the password. The most optimal way to do this is to trim the repeating char groups that are closest to the number 3 and its multiples, as it only takes one step to both trim closer to desired length and remove a repeating char group. For example: 'aaaaaa' needs two chars to become non repeating 'aaxaax'. We sort the detected repeating char groups by modulo 3 and size, decrement it, filtering out any groups smaller than 3. Performance could be improved by not just sorting the chars at the end but inteligently resetting the index, but for this small of an input it shouldn't be a problem at all. We repeat the steps until we trimmed the password enough, then just calculate the remaining repeating steps and overlaps. 

# Code
```
use core::cmp::max;

impl Solution {
    pub fn strong_password_checker(password: String) -> i32 {
        let mut has_digit = false;
        let mut has_lower = false;
        let mut has_upper = false;
        let mut repeating_chars: Vec<usize> = Vec::new();
        let mut prev_char = '-';
        let mut char_count = 0;

        // initial state analysis for simplicity of checks
        for c in password.chars() {
            if c.is_lowercase() {
                has_lower = true;
            }
            if c.is_uppercase() {
                has_upper = true;
            }
            if c.is_digit(10) {
                has_digit = true;
            }

            // add repeating char groups counts
            if c == prev_char {
                char_count += 1;
            } else {
                // push if large enough and reset
                if char_count >= 2 {
                    repeating_chars.push(char_count);
                }
                prev_char = c;
                char_count = 0;
            }
        }
        // add the final group if needed
        if char_count > 1 {
            repeating_chars.push(char_count);
        }

        // cases of missing lower/upper/digit
        let mut steps_to_correct: i32 = 0;
        if !has_digit {
            steps_to_correct += 1;
        }
        if !has_lower {
            steps_to_correct += 1;
        }
        if !has_upper {
            steps_to_correct += 1;
        }

        // resolve if too short, trivial because we can always avoid repeats by adding correctly
        if password.len() < 6 {
            return max(6 - password.len() as i32, steps_to_correct);
        }


        // how much to trim
        let mut delet_to_correct: i32 = 0;
        // if too long we must take steps to shorten, overlap possible with corrections of repeating char groups
        if password.len() > 20 {
            delet_to_correct = (password.len() - 20) as i32;
            let mut delet_bucket = delet_to_correct;

            // sort first by modulo then size to find most optimal places to trim chars
            repeating_chars.sort_by_key(|&rch| ((rch + 1) % 3, rch));

            // remove as many repeating_chars as possible with delet_to_correct, starting with most
            // optimal places to deduct, then filtering out as we go. Most optimal is the ones that
            // either remove the repeating constrains ('aaa' -> 'aa' aka 3->2) then the ones that change
            // the number of needed steps to repair (the ones closest to modulo 3)
            while delet_bucket > 0 && repeating_chars.len() > 0 {
                repeating_chars[0] -= 1;
                delet_bucket -= 1;
                repeating_chars.retain(|&ch| ch > 1 as usize);
                repeating_chars.sort_by_key(|&rch| ((rch + 1) % 3, rch));

            }
        }
        // if we have repeating we must break them up, but with a
        // replace we can combine multiple steps into one: 'aaa0aa' -> 'aAa0aa' (1 step)
        // first we calculate how many steps we need to remove all the repeating,
        // then we overlap those with needed steps for non repeating fixes
        let mut repeat_correct: i32 = 0;
        for rep in repeating_chars {
            repeat_correct += ((rep + 1) / 3) as i32;
        }

        if repeat_correct > 0 {
            repeat_correct = max(0, repeat_correct - steps_to_correct);
        }

        steps_to_correct + repeat_correct + delet_to_correct
    }
}
