solutions.content:
For approching this problem we have to know xor's property.
xor is 1 when two bits are diffrent
(`0^1 = 1 and 1^0 = 1`)
and we need maximum xor so we will greedely try to set all MSBs from left in our answer if possible.

prefix variable in our solution will help us to get first i bits from nums
(prefix will grow like : `10000 -> 11000 -> 11100 -> 11110 -> 11111`)

then we are storing these prefix bits of nums in a hash set
n & prefix  will give us first i bits of nums
for example if `n = 25 -> 11001 and prefix is 11100 `
so n & prefix will get us ->` 11000 `( first i bits of this number n which is 110)

now if we want to set ith bit of answer
let say` c = ans | (1<<i)` (this is how we set ith bit of any number)
then we have to check if there exits two number whose prefixs till i bits
will give us xor value = c
, `a ^ b = c `
as we fixed c and when iterating in set we will fix one number `a` then
`b` will be` a ^ c` , { as `a^b = c` then `a^c = b` }
just like two sum if we got a, does b exist which give us c
so we have to check do b exists in our set
if yes our ans will have this ith bit = 1, thus `ans = c`
else answer will remain same as this bit will 0 otherwise

**Below is c++ code :**
```
