solutions.content:
>Intuitively, 
```
for i 0 .. n
  for j i+1 .. n
    overallMax = max(overallMall, nums[i] ^ nums[j])
```
> That takes O(n^2) time.

> However, O(n) time is required. 
> 
> In other words, we have to enable nums[i] to know **which element paired with itself can form the maximum XOR**. Then we calculate the maximum XOR for each num and aggregate the overall maximum.


> Given nums[i], how does the target element (paired with nums[i] that makes the maximum XOR) look like?
The target element should share shortest common prefixes  with nums[i].

> How do we tell which element shares the shortest common prefixes with nums[i]?
> Prefix tree

> What is a node in the prefix tree?
> zero means the bit is not set
> one means the bit is set
> the height of a node indicates which bit it is

```
class Solution {
    private Node root;

    public int findMaximumXOR(int[] nums) {
        root = new Node();

        // Build a trie from nums
        for (int num : nums) {
            insert(num);
        }

        int overallMax = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
        // Search for num in the trie, and get its maximum XOR to update the overal maximum
        for (int num : nums) {
            overallMax = Math.max(overallMax, search(num));
        }

        return overallMax;        
    }

    private void insert(int num) {
        Node ptr = root;
        // i indicates bit position for the rightmost bit is at position 0
        // i also indicates node's depth in trie, i.e. the length of the path from root to the end
        for (int i = 31; i >= 0; i--) {
            int val = (num >> i) & 1;
            if (val == 1) {
                if (ptr.one == null) {
                    ptr.one = new Node();
                }
                ptr = ptr.one;
            } else {
                if (ptr.zero == null) {
                    ptr.zero = new Node();
                }
                ptr = ptr.zero;
            }
        }
    }

    private int search(int num) {
        Node ptr = root;
        int maxXOR = 0;
        for (int i = 31; i >= 0; i--) {
            int val = (num >> i) & 1;
            if (val == 1) {
                if (ptr.zero != null) {
                    ptr = ptr.zero;
                    maxXOR += (1 << i);
                } else {
                    ptr = ptr.one;
                }
            } else {
                if (ptr.one != null) {
                    ptr = ptr.one;
                    maxXOR += (1 << i);
                } else {
                    ptr = ptr.zero;
                }
            }
        }
        return maxXOR;
    }

    class Node {
        Node zero;
        Node one;
    }
}
```

