solutions.content:
TRUST ME, the code looks complicated, but its really easy to understand. I have made it as readable as possible.
My code, works by using the concept of binary trees. Except, that the node do not need to store any value. I have defined a simple structure with 2 simple pointers, left and right. The left pointer indicates the bit value 0, and the right pointer indicates the bit value 1. So here are the steps that I followed,
* 1. First, we find the maximum value from the list by scanning through the array once, I have used the variable name "max" for this purpose.
* 2. Next, we find the index of the highest possible 1 bit in the max variable. I have used the variable name "maxbit" for this purpose.
* 3. We then construct a Binary tree from the input array and create a left node if we encounter a 0, and create a right node if we encounter a 1. We do this for all the numbers provided in the input array.
* 4. The binary tree gives us a base model that we can now work upon. Now, to find the 2 numbers that gives us the maximum XOR, we have to find 2 complimentary bits, or in other words, 2 complimentary branches for the current node. Let me explain this in detail.
* 5. We first initialise 2 pointers to traverse the binary tree, I have used the names "pt1" and "pt2" for this purpose. In the beginning, both these pointers are assigned to the head or as I have called it, the "begin" node. If both pointers move in opposite directions, then we can have the highest possible XORed value, since XOR provides a 1 bit for a complimentary input.
* 6. Now lets look at the available options that we have to work with, let me create a table that provides all the possible options available for these pointers, 
*                           pt1                                          pt2                                    Action
*                  Only left node available                       Only left node available              Move pt1 left and pt2 left. (As there isnt any other option available)
*                  Only left node available                      Only Right node available              Move pt1 left and pt2 right. (As these are complimentary operations, we add 1 bit at the current index of the answer)
*                  Only left node available                   Both left and Right node available        Move pt1 left and pt2 right. (As these are complimentary operations, we add 1 bit at the current index of the answer)
*                  Only Right node available                      Only left node available              Move pt1 right and pt2 left. (As these are complimentary operations, we add 1 bit at the current index of the answer)
*                  Only Right node available                      Only Right node available             Move pt1 right and pt2 right. (As there isnt any other option available)
*                  Only Right node available                  Both left and Right node available        Move pt1 right and pt2 left. (As these are complimentary operations, we add 1 bit at the current index of the answer)
*                Both left and Right node available                Only left node available             Move pt1 right and pt2 left. (As these are complimentary operations, we add 1 bit at the current index of the answer)
*                Both left and Right node available                Only right node available            Move pt1 left and pt2 right. (As these are complimentary operations, we add 1 bit at the current index of the answer)
*                Both left and Right node available          Both left and Right node available     We use recursion here, by first moving pt1 left and pt2 right, and then pt1 right and pt2 left.
*  7. In the last option, we can see that, as we do not have any clue of where to move, so we test both the options available to us. We first move pt1 left and pt2 right, get the answer for this choice, and then move pt1 right and pt2 left and capture the answer. We then compare the results and pick the maximum value. As this is a recursive call, we end the loop here. 
*  8. Here, the path followed by pt1, corresponds to the first value that needs to be XORed, and the path followed by pt2 corresponds to the second value. In case you need to find these values, We can create 2 more variables in the "findMaxXOR" function and capture the path followed by pt1 and pt2, we can then XOR these 2 values to get the final result. In fact, this is exactly what I had done previously, before realising that there was a better alternative. 
*  9. I would like to urge you to read my code, the "addnode" function isn't important to understand the concept, just assume that it creates a new node and returns the node with both left and right values equal to NULL.
	# Code
```
#define MAX (1000)

struct node{
    struct node * left;
    struct node * right;
};


struct node * arr;
struct node * addnode(int *size, int *maxsize)
{
    if((*size) >= (*maxsize))
    {
        (*maxsize) += MAX;
        arr = (struct node *)malloc((*maxsize) * sizeof(struct node));
    }
    (arr + ((*size) % MAX))->left = NULL;
    (arr + ((*size) % MAX))->right = NULL;
    (*size) += 1;
    return (arr + (((*size) - 1) % MAX));
}

int findMaxXOR(struct node *pt1, struct node *pt2, int maxbit);

int findMaximumXOR(int* nums, int numsSize){
    if(numsSize < 2)
        return 0;
    int max = 0;
    for(int i = 0 ; i < numsSize ; i++)
        if(nums[max] < nums[i])
            max = i;

    int maxbit = 30;
    for(maxbit = 0 ; maxbit < 31 ; maxbit++)
        if((nums[max] >> maxbit) == 1)
            break;

    int nodesize = 0, nodemaxsize = 0;
    arr = NULL;
    struct node *begin = addnode(&nodesize, &nodemaxsize);

    for(int i = 0 ; i < numsSize; i++)
    {
        struct node *temp = begin;
        for(int j = maxbit; j >= 0 ; j--)
        {
            if((1 << j) & nums[i])
            {
                if(temp->right == NULL)
                    temp->right = addnode(&nodesize, &nodemaxsize);
                temp = temp->right;
            }
            else
            {
                if(temp->left == NULL)
                    temp->left = addnode(&nodesize, &nodemaxsize);
                temp = temp->left;
            }
        }
    }

    int ans = findMaxXOR(begin, begin, maxbit);

    free(begin);

    return ans;
}


int findMaxXOR(struct node *pt1, struct node *pt2, int index)
{
    int ans = 0;
    while(index >= 0)
    {
        int pt1State = 0, pt2State = 0;
        if(pt1->left != NULL)
            pt1State = 1;
        if(pt1->right != NULL)
            pt1State += 2;
        if(pt2->left != NULL)
            pt2State = 1;
        if(pt2->right != NULL)
            pt2State += 2;
        switch(pt1State)      //if pt1State's value is 1, then only left node is avaibale, if 2, then only right node is available, if 3, then both are available. (for pt1)
        {
            case 1:
                pt1 = pt1->left;
                if(pt2State == 1)
                    pt2 = pt2->left;
                else
                {
                    pt2 = pt2->right;
                    ans |= (1 << index);   //As pt1 and pt2's action is complimentary, we add 1 to the index of the answer variable.
                }
                break;
            case 2:
                pt1 = pt1->right;
                if(pt2State == 2)
                    pt2 = pt2->right;
                else
                {
                    pt2 = pt2->left;
                    ans |= (1 << index);   //As pt1 and pt2's action is complimentary, we add 1 to the index of the answer variable.
                }
                break;
            case 3:
                ans |= (1 << index);   //As pt1 and pt2's action is complimentary, we add 1 to the index of the answer variable.
                switch(pt2State)
                {
                    case 1:
                        pt1 = pt1->right;
                        pt2 = pt2->left;
                        break;
                    case 2:
                        pt1 = pt1->left;
                        pt2 = pt2->right;
                        break;
                    case 3:
                        {
                            if(pt1 == pt2)                        //check for starting condition, where both pt1 and pt2 are equal to "begin"
                                return (findMaxXOR(pt1->left, pt2->right, index - 1) | ans);

                            int ans1 = findMaxXOR(pt1->left, pt2->right, index - 1);
                            int ans2 = findMaxXOR(pt1->right, pt2->left, index - 1);
                            if(ans1 > ans2)
                                return (ans1 | ans);
                            else
                                return (ans2 | ans);
                        }
                        break;
                }
                break;
        }
        index--;
    }
    return ans;
}
